[Text adapted from guiding document for demonstrating compliance with the obligations provided for in Articles 53 and 55 of the AI Act] 

Signatories of the Code of Practice for General-Purpose AI models commit to:
1. Creating, implementing update a Safety and Security Framework outlining systemic risk management processes. This includes defining trigger points for additional model evaluations and establishing risk acceptance criteria. Review Safety and Security Framework at least once per year.
2. Following a structured process to identify risks to public health, safety, security, fundamental rights, and society. Providers must develop specific "systemic risk scenarios" for each identified risk.
3. Gathering model-independent information, conducting state-of-the-art model evaluations, and estimating the probability and severity of potential harm.
4. Specifying criteria to decide if identified risks are acceptable and only proceed with development or market placement if they meet these standards.
5. Implementing appropriate measures such as filtering training data, fine-tuning for refusal of harmful requests, and staging model access to vetted users.
6. Defining a "Security Goal" to protect against specific threat actors. This involves securing model parameters through encryption, access management, and protection against insider threats.
7. Creating and maintaining a Safety and Security Model Report for the AI Office before placing a model on the market, describing its architecture, identified risks, and implemented mitigation strategies. In addition to internal model evaluations, providers shall ensure that adequately qualified independent external evaluators conduct model evaluations.
8. Defining clear systemic risk responsibility allocation, through risk oversight, ownership, and assurance across all organisational levels. Signatories must promote a healthy risk culture and allocate adequate resources to these functions.
9. Implementing processes to track, document, and report serious incidents to the AI Office without undue delay. Reporting timelines range from 2 to 15 days depending on the severity of the harm (e.g., death or critical infrastructure disruption).
10. Keeping detailed technical documentation for at least 10 years and publish summarised, public versions of frameworks and model reports.

1.Where a general-purpose AI model meets the condition referred to in Article 51(1), point (a), the relevant provider shall notify the Commission without delay and in any event within two weeks after that requirement is met or it becomes known that it will be met. That notification shall include the information necessary to demonstrate that the relevant requirement has been met. If the Commission becomes aware of a general-purpose AI model presenting systemic risks of which it has not been notified, it may decide to designate it as a model with systemic risk.
2.The provider of a general-purpose AI model that meets the condition referred to in Article 51(1), point (a), may present, with its notification, sufficiently substantiated arguments to demonstrate that, exceptionally, although it meets that requirement, the general-purpose AI model does not present, due to its specific characteristics, systemic risks and therefore should not be classified as a general-purpose AI model with systemic risk.

